00:00:48.640 --> 00:00:50.480
This is a really
important question.

00:00:50.480 --> 00:00:54.040
How do you know
what channel is at--

00:00:54.040 --> 00:00:56.260
how do you know what ion
a particular channel is

00:00:56.260 --> 00:00:58.150
conducting?

00:00:58.150 --> 00:00:59.650
It's actually hard to determine.

00:00:59.650 --> 00:01:05.650
There are various ways to do
it, where you can specifically

00:01:05.650 --> 00:01:08.380
label the ion, or
follow a particular ion,

00:01:08.380 --> 00:01:11.470
and address whether or not
it's getting into a cell

00:01:11.470 --> 00:01:14.200
or across a membrane, when
there's a particular ion

00:01:14.200 --> 00:01:15.550
channel present.

00:01:15.550 --> 00:01:17.620
But it's not completely trivial.

00:01:17.620 --> 00:01:20.140
One of the things I didn't have
time to go through with you,

00:01:20.140 --> 00:01:22.670
but which is one of
the PowerPoints though,

00:01:22.670 --> 00:01:27.730
is the fact that ion channels
are really selective.

00:01:27.730 --> 00:01:32.560
And they don't conduct ions
on the basis of size, OK?

00:01:32.560 --> 00:01:37.540
So you're not going to get
a large ion channel that

00:01:37.540 --> 00:01:41.620
could accommodate a large ion,
also accommodating a small ion.

00:01:41.620 --> 00:01:45.340
It's not a matter about of
just opening up a space.

00:01:45.340 --> 00:01:47.620
There are also
charge considerations

00:01:47.620 --> 00:01:52.060
where the ions actually
interact with the molecules

00:01:52.060 --> 00:01:55.840
in the channel, in the actual
pore through the membrane.

00:01:55.840 --> 00:01:59.860
And it's that interaction which
selects for a particular ion.

00:01:59.860 --> 00:02:03.970
But this notion of exactly what
ions channels are conducting

00:02:03.970 --> 00:02:08.590
has been many, many
decades of work.

00:02:08.590 --> 00:02:10.609
And what I've written
up here is correct.

00:02:10.609 --> 00:02:12.400
But if you want to
explore it more with me,

00:02:12.400 --> 00:02:14.290
